}} ''' øAmrƒÅn''' ({{lang-ar|ÿπŸÖÿ±ÿßŸÜ}}; [[Ancient South Arabian script|Old South Arabian]]: '''ê©≤ê©£ê©ßê©¨''' '' ømrn'') is a small city in western central [[Yemen]]. It is the capital of the [['Amran Governorate]], and was formerly in the [[Sana'a Governorate]]. It is located {{convert|52.9|km}} by road northwest of the Yemeni capital of [[Sana'a]].<ref name="GM">{{cite map|title= Maps|publisher=[[Google Maps]]}}</ref> According to the 2004 census it had a population of 76,863, and an estimated population of 90,792 in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&lng=de&des=wg&geo=380398394&srt=pnan&col=adhoq&msz=1500&men=gpro&lng=en|title=Amran|publisher=World Gazetteer|accessdate=13 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515215832/http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=|archive-date=15 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==History and architecture== [[File:Amran.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Traditional mud-built house.]] The founding of the town dates back to the era of the South Arabian [[Himyarite Kingdom]]. At the time of the Sabaean kingdom, the town blossomed into a fortress. A series of [[Amran Tablets|bronze plaques]] from that time were found in the town in the mid-nineteenth century and are now in the [[British Museum]]. In particular, in the seventh century it was the great city of valour during the clashes against the Sabeans, a plurality of regionally based tribes. Remains of carved stones that belonged to former temples and palaces bear witness today of past glory. A large stone inscription is found in the western city gate (Bab al-Kabir). The old [[souq]] is noted for its stone columns.<ref name="H√§m√§l√§inen1999">{{cite book|last=H√§m√§l√§inen|first=Pertti|title=Yemen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RCYuAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=13 April 2012|date=1 August 1999|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-0-86442-603-1}}</ref> øAmram is completely surrounded by walls which date to 1720. The surrounding landscape is dominated by terraced landscapes with stone walls to counteract erosion of fertile arable land.
==Economic development== The road through the city from Sana'a was modernized following Chinese investment and is over {{convert|200|km|abbr=on}} long, and the old medical centre has been transformed into a small public hospital.<ref name="McLaughlin2008">{{cite book|last=McLaughlin|first=Daniel|title=Yemen: The Bradt Travel Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg=PA107|accessdate=13 April 2012|date=12 February 2008|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-84162-212-5|page=107}}</ref> The city is located in a fertile area in what was the centre of the area's coffee industry.<ref name="McCullochHaskel1845">{{cite book|last1=McCulloch|first1=John Ramsay|last2=Haskel|first2=Daniel|title=M'Culloch's Universal gazetteer: Dictionary, geographical, statistical, and historical, of the various countries, places, and principal natural objects in the world|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DfoRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA93|accessdate=15 April 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1845|publisher=Harper & brothers|pages=93‚Äì}}</ref>
